                             urlgulp
                             =======

 privacy tool - pretty print urls requests from http traffic on the network
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

urlgulp's goal is to make it easy to answer questions like:
  "what happens on the network when browsing site foo.com ?"
(or any other program for that matter)

It gives a quick and easy to read summary of network activity around an
http request, highlighting potential issues with third party content
(3pe's). opening of non http tcp connections and dns traffic is also
monitored.

At the end of each interval (time or key press based) requests are grouped
by host and highlighted, with pictures and css collapsed by default for
clarity. 

It makes it easy to visualize:
- third party domains involved
- url query strings
- javascript resources loaded
- leaked referrer
- use of dns aliases to 3rd party domain
- post requests
- user agent used


Installation:
- dependencies: perl, tcpdump, urlsnarf (dsniff)
- run as root.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Usage: urlgulp [options] [-i interface]

display mode:
  -k            wait for key press to display (default).
  -f            display every interval seconds.
  -w            display after interval seconds of silence.

other options:
  -d <interval> set display interval for -f and -w (default: 5s).
  -u            show user agent used for each request.
  -l            show legend.
  -q            quiet mode. Don't log urls, only domains.
  -r            raw url mode. just dump it all, no url coloring, grouping or truncating.
  -v            debug mode (use twice for more).
  --tcp-only    track tcp connections only (no urls)
                will show which IP addresses are actually being contacted,
                useful to check whether a remote proxy is really being used or not.
  --version     show version.

